Stability of endoperoxides depends on molecular structure and can be tuned by chemical modification from several hours to several days. The lifetime also depends strongly on temperature. This creates a practical “store-and-release” concept: reactive oxygen can be stored at low temperature and then released on demand by thermal decomposition. Such behaviour can be used as a method for controlled singlet oxygen delivery in photodynamic therapy, including in biological media at room temperature.

